\cb3 5. 	What is a stateless protocol? \cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb4 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 A stateless protocol is a system of rules that does not keep track of the requests that came before or after one another. It handles each request independently. An HTTP protocol is an example of a stateless protocol. This is the opposite of a stateful protocol, which does keep track of each requests and evaluates and processes them in relation to each other.\
\
Therefore, a stateless protocol request would have to be specific in its result-set: \
